a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes A B C :: "real mat"
assumes h0 : "A = mat_of_rows_list [[2, 0], [5, -3]]"
and h1 : "B = mat_of_rows_list [[8, -2], [1, 1]]"
and h2 : "C = A * B"
shows  "C = mat_of_rows_list [[16, -4], [37, -13]]"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Compute $\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\ 5 & -3 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 8 & -2 \\ 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}.$ The final Answer is \begin{pmatrix} 16 & -4 \\ 37 & -13 \end{pmatrix}
 ### Proof
 We have that \[\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\ 5 & -3 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 8 & -2 \\ 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (2)(8) + (0)(1) & (2)(-2) + (0)(1) \\ (5)(8) + (-3)(1) & (5)(-2) + (-3)(1) \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 16 & -4 \\ 37 & -13 \end{pmatrix}}.\]
 *)

theorem
fixes A B C :: "real mat"
assumes h0 : "A = mat_of_rows_list [[2, 0], [5, -3]]"
and h1 : "B = mat_of_rows_list [[8, -2], [1, 1]]"
and h2 : "C = A * B"
shows  "C = mat_of_rows_list [[16, -4], [37, -13]]"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Calculate the product of the two matrices: A = [[2, 0], [5, -3]] and B = [[8, -2], [1, 1]]. The final result is C = [[16, -4], [37, -13]].
